Keith E. Sonderling of Florida has been nominated to be a Member of the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) for the remainder of a five-year term. He is currently the Deputy Administrator of the United States Department of Labor's Wage and Hour Division. Sonderling has extensive experience in labor and employment law, previously practicing at the Gunster Law Firm in West Palm Beach, Florida. He received his B.S. from the University of Florida and his J.D. from Nova Southeastern University.

Charlotte A. Burrows of the District of Columbia has also been nominated to be a Member of the EEOC for the remainder of a five-year term. She has been serving as a Commissioner with the EEOC since January 2015. Burrows has held various positions in the United States Department of Justice, including Associate Deputy Attorney General and Deputy Chief for the Civil Rights Division. She has also worked as the general counsel for civil and constitutional rights for United States Senator Edward M. Kennedy. Burrows has a degree in A.B. from Princeton University and a J.D. from Yale Law School.